\textbf{Determine eigenvalues of $B=10A$}

We will first find the eigenvalues of the matrix
$B=\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
8 & 5  \\ 
2 & 5
\end{array} \right]$ to avoid dealing with fractions. The eigenvalues of
the matrix \emph{A}, will simply be $\frac{1}{10}$ of this integer
matrix \emph{B}.

To find the eigenvalues we calculate as usual:

\begin{align*}
\det\left( \left[ \begin{array}{cc}
8-t & 5  \\ 
2 & 5-t
\end{array} \right]  \right) &=(8-t)(5-t) - (5)(2) \\
 &= t^2 - 13t + 30\\
&= (t-3)(t-10)\\
&=0\end{align*}

\textbf{Determine eigenvectors of $B=10A$}

For the eigenvectors with \textbf{eigenvalue 3} we look at
$\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
8-3 & 5  \\ 
2 & 5-3
\end{array} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{cc}
5 & 5  \\ 
2 & 2
\end{array} \right]$ which gives the eigenvector
$\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
1 \\ 
-1 
\end{array} \right]$.

For the \textbf{eigenvalue 10}, we look at the $\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
-2 & 5  \\ 
2 & -5
\end{array} \right]$ which gives the eigenvectors
$\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
5 \\ 
2 
\end{array} \right]$.

\textbf{Eigenvalues and eigenvectors of $A$}

For the matrix \emph{A} this means that \emph{A} has the

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  eigenvalue $\frac{3}{10}$ with eigenvector
  v\_1=\textbackslash{}left{[} \textbackslash{}begin\{array\}\{cc\}
\end{itemize}

1 \textbackslash{}\textbackslash{} -1 \textbackslash{}end\{array\}
\textbackslash{}right{]}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  eigenvalue $1$ with eigenvector v\_2=\textbackslash{}left{[}
  \textbackslash{}begin\{array\}\{cc\}
\end{itemize}

5 \textbackslash{}\textbackslash{} 2 \textbackslash{}end\{array\}
\textbackslash{}right{]}

\textbf{Find $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$ such that $x_0 = av_1+bv_2$}

To find the closed formulae for the components of
\textbf{x}\textsubscript{n} we decompose the vector $x_0$ into a sum of
the eigenvectors of \emph{A}. To do so, we use the extended matrix:

\begin{align*}[v_1 \  v_2\ |\ x_0] =  \left[ \begin{array}{cc|c}
1 & 5 & 4 \\ 
-1 & 2 & 1 \\ 
\end{array} \right]  \sim \left[ \begin{array}{cc|c}
1 & 5 & 4 \\ 
0 & 7 & 5 \\ 
\end{array} \right] \sim \left[ \begin{array}{cc|c}
1 & 0 & 3/7 \\ 
0 & 1 & 5/7 \\ 
\end{array} \right]\end{align*}

Thus \emph{a} = 3/7 and \emph{b} = 5/7 and therefore

\begin{align*}\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
4 \\ 
1 
\end{array} \right]  = 3/7 \left[ \begin{array}{cc}
1 \\ 
-1 
\end{array} \right]  + 5/7\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
5 \\ 
2 
\end{array} \right].\end{align*}

\emph{' Computing $x_n$}'

We can now compute $x_n$ as follows:

\begin{align*}
 x_n = A^nx_0 &= A^n\left(\frac{3}{7} \left[ \begin{array}{cc}
1 \\ 
-1 
\end{array} \right]  + \frac{5}{7}\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
5 \\ 
2 
\end{array} \right]\right) \\&= \frac{3}{7} A^n\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
1 \\ 
-1 
\end{array} \right]  + \frac{5}{7}A^n\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
5 \\ 
2 
\end{array} \right]  \\ &= \frac{3}{7}\frac{3^n}{10^n} \left[ \begin{array}{cc}
1 \\ 
-1 
\end{array} \right]  + \frac{5}{7}1^n\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
5 \\ 
2 
\end{array} \right] \end{align*}
